data.title: U.S. stock futures rise ahead of busy week on Wall Street. Dow Jones +0.56%, S&P 500 +0.78%, Nasdaq 100 +1.14%. Novartis to acquire Avidity Biosciences for $12 billion. Yammer boosts after merger announcement.
data.description: U.S. stock futures rose on Monday, with major benchmark indices higher ahead of various key events. Notable ones include the earnings reports of five Magnificent 7 constituents like Microsoft, Alphabet and Meta on Wednesday, along with Apple and Amazon on Thursday. The Federal Reserve will decide on interest rates on Wednesday, coinciding with President Trump's meeting with Xi Jinping on Thursday in South Korea, focused on averting a 100% tariff threat. The 10-year Treasury bond yielded 4.03%, with a 3.5% two-year bond. CME Group's FedWatch tool projects a 96.7% chance of the Federal Reserve cutting interest rates. Futures showed a positive change for Dow Jones (+0.56%), S&P 500 (+0.78%), Nasdaq 100 (+1.14%), and Russell 2000 (+1.03%). The SPDR S&P 500 ETF Trust (SPY) and Invesco QQQ Trust ETF (QQQ) also rose in premarket trading. Avidity Biosciences Inc. surged 42.56% after Novartis AG agreed to acquire it for $12 billion, while Plymouth Industrial REIT agreed to be acquired by Makarora Management LP and Ares Alternative Credit Funds.

data.title: MSG Sports (NYSA: MSGS) Q1 loss at 37 cents/share, better than estimated 88 cents loss. Revenue down 26% to $39.5M.
data.description: Madison Square Garden Sports Corp. (NYSE: MSGS) saw a drop in shares following the release of their first-quarter financial results. The company reported a loss of 37 cents per share, surpassing analyst predictions of an 88 cents loss, although worse compared to last year's loss of 31 cents per share. Revenue also fell by 26% to $39.5 million, missing the anticipated $41.30 million, mainly due to a significant decrease in revenues from league distributions totaling $11.4 million. This decline was attributed to lower league distributions not related to national media rights fees. Additionally, the company saw a decrease in certain league distributions, unrelated to national media rights fees.

data.title: InventHelp inventor from Thomasville, GA creates multi-language call controller solution for patients (MHO-492) - Oct. 31, 2025.
data.description: In Pittsburgh on October 31, 2025, a registered nurse from Thomasville, Georgia shared her invention aimed at helping patients of diverse language backgrounds to navigate medical call systems. The inventor expressed her motivation to streamline communication by simplifying the understanding of buttons and functions on the call system controller. This innovation addresses the obstacle faced by non-English speaking patients, enhancing their access to medical assistance. The invention could potentially benefit a considerable number of individuals requiring medical attention in healthcare facilities.
